The smooth command, sm, is an algorithm for reducing variations in
loudness, or dynamic range, in an audio passage.  The sm command may be
qualified by one or a comma separated pair of block addresses to limit
the action to a portion of the session.  It may be followed by a space,
and a comma separated triple of arguments if desired.  The first of these
is the time span in seconds over wich smoothing is computed. The second
is a digit, 0 or higher, indicating how much suppression to apply to
very weak signals.  The third parameter is the dynamic range in decibels
signifying that an audio passage is already sufficiently smooth.  It is
used to cancel smoothing for material longer than 20 seconds when there
is no benefit to be gained from smoothing, which is computationally
costly to perform.

Privately smoothing aims at a uniform loudness no higher than the default
RMS value, using only linear adjustments.  Publicly smoothing relaxes
the requirement of linearity, in order to achieve the default loudness
more aggressively.  Smoothing privately yields better quality, perhaps at
lower average loudness.  Smoothing publicly yields more uniform loudness
across a number of audio files, perhaps at the cost of introducing some
nonlinear distortions.  The pub command is used to toggle between public
and private smoothing.

